Feyisayo Popoola At the end of the first week in August, equity investors lost N157.7bn as bearish sentiments dominated the market. Continental Reinsurance Plc topped the losers’ table as it saw its share price drop from N1.72 to N1.39. The market capitalisation of equities listed on the Nigerian Stock Exchange dropped to N13.307tn on Friday from the N13.465tn it closed at the previous week. Though the banking index recorded the highest decline last week, down by 6.05 per cent, insurance companies emerged the top two losers during the week. Law Union and Rock Insurance Company Plc emerged the second biggest loser during the week as its share price dropped by 17.02 per cent to close the week at 39 kobo. A total turnover of 1.081 billion shares worth N12.014bn in 16,246 deals were traded last week by investors on the floor of the Exchange, in contrast to a total of 759.266 million shares valued at N14.038bn that exchanged hands the previous week in 16,209 deals. The financial services industry (measured by volume) led the activity chart with 900.334 million shares valued at N9.076bn traded in 8,693 deals, thus contributing 83.30 per cent and 75.54 per cent to the total equity turnover volume and value, respectively. The conglomerates industry followed with 51.224 million shares worth N64.388m in 897 deals. The third place was occupied by the consumer goods industry with a turnover of 40.906 million shares worth N946.210m in 3,090 deals. Trading in the top three equities, namely Sterling Bank Plc, Guaranty Trust Bank Plc and Access Bank Plc (measured by volume), accounted for 511.856 million shares worth N6.133bn in 2,074 deals, contributing 47.36 per cent and 51.05 per cent to the total equity turnover volume and value, respectively. The NSE All Share Index and market capitalisation both depreciated by 1.17 per cent to close the week at 27,306.81bps and N13.307tn, respectively. Similarly, all other indices finished lower with the exception of the industrial goods index, which appreciated by 1.32 per cent while the ASeM index closed flat. The banking index, dragged by losses in Unity Bank Plc, FBN Holdings Plc and Zenith Bank Plc, declined by 6.05 per cent. The insurance index depreciated by 3.88 per cent while the oil and gas index declined by 1.62 per cent due to major sell-offs witnessed in Forte Oil Plc. The consumer goods index shed 0.65 per cent on the back of major losses in May and Baker Nigeria Plc. On the flip side, the industrial goods index emerged the lone gainer, up by 1.32 per cent on the back of gains recorded in Cement Company of Northern Nigeria Plc, Dangote Flour Mills Plc and Lafarge Africa Plc. Twelve equities appreciated in price last week while 43 equities depreciated in price, compared to 32 gainers and 27 losers recorded during the previous week. The top gainers were Cement Company of Northern Nigeria, Dangote Flour Mills, B.O.C. Gases Plc, NCR Nigeria Plc and AXA Mansard Insurance Plc. The top losers were Continental Reinsurance, Law Union and Rock Insurance, Unity Bank, Forte Oil and Academy Press Plc. Copyright PUNCH.                
